@satra, can you take a look?

Conda-forge tried to update to 3.2 (https://github.com/conda-forge/h5py-feedstock/pull/86) but got test failures. It appears that their HDF5 has the ROS3 driver enabled. All the tracebacks I've spotted end here:

```
    @property
    @with_phil
    def driver(self):
        """Low-level HDF5 file driver used to open file"""
        drivers = {h5fd.SEC2: 'sec2',
                   h5fd.STDIO: 'stdio',
                   h5fd.CORE: 'core',
                   h5fd.FAMILY: 'family',
                   h5fd.WINDOWS: 'windows',
                   h5fd.MPIO: 'mpio',
                   h5fd.MPIPOSIX: 'mpiposix',
                   h5fd.fileobj_driver: 'fileobj'}
        if ros3:
>           drivers[h5fd.ROS3] = 'ros3'
E           AttributeError: module 'h5py.h5fd' has no attribute 'ROS3'
```

When writing a string, the size set in the HDF5Type does not include the terminating NULL although this is required according to HDF5: `String or character datatypes: The size set for a string datatype should include space for the null-terminator character, otherwise it will not be stored on (or retrieved from) disk` [Datatype-SetSize](https://support.hdfgroup.org/HDF5/doc/RM/RM_H5T.html#Datatype-SetSize)

Example:

```
import h5py
import numpy
f=h5py.File("test.h5")
f.attrs["fooStr"] = numpy.string_("1234")
f.close()
```

bash:

```
h5dump test.h5
```

> > HDF5 "test.h5" {
> > GROUP "/" {
> >    ATTRIBUTE "fooStr" {
> >       DATATYPE  H5T_STRING {
> >          STRSIZE 4;
> >          STRPAD H5T_STR_NULLPAD;
> >          CSET H5T_CSET_ASCII;
> >          CTYPE H5T_C_S1;
> >       }
> >       DATASPACE  SCALAR
> >       DATA {
> >       (0): "1234"
> >       }
> >    }
> > }

Expected:

> > HDF5 "test.h5" {
> > GROUP "/" {
> >    ATTRIBUTE "fooStr" {
> >       DATATYPE  H5T_STRING {
> >          STRSIZE 5;
> >          STRPAD H5T_STR_NULLPAD;
> >          CSET H5T_CSET_ASCII;
> >          CTYPE H5T_C_S1;
> >       }
> >       DATASPACE  SCALAR
> >       DATA {
> >       (0): "1234"
> >       }
> >    }
> > }

If I create a committed type with a VLEN string, it does not get saved correctly to the file.
E.g.

```
import h5py
import numpy as np
f = h5py.File("named_type.h5", "w")
fields = []
fields.append(('field_1', h5py.special_dtype(vlen=str)))
fields.append(('field_2', np.int32))
dt = np.dtype(fields)
f['mytype'] = np.dtype(dt)
f.close()
```

This runs ok, but if I do a h5dump on the file, it looks like the vlen string got saved as an Opaque:

```
HDF5 "named_type.h5" {
GROUP "/" {
   DATATYPE "mytype" H5T_COMPOUND {
      H5T_OPAQUE {
         OPAQUE_TAG "PYTHON:OBJECT";
      } "field_1";
      H5T_STD_I32LE "field_2";
   }
}
}
```

The documentation for File says:
class File(name, mode=None, driver=None, libver=None, userblock_size, *_kwds)
when it should say:
class File(name, mode=None, driver=None, libver=None, userblock_size=None, *_kwds)

_Original author: andy.sal...@gmail.com (October 30, 2012 19:46:00)_

Hi,

we are trying to migrate our code from h5py 1.3.0/python2.4 to
2.0.1/python2.7 and there is one thing that confuses us. This
is apparently related to the change described in &quot;What's new
in 2.0&quot; regarding &quot;Array scalars now always returned when 
indexing a dataset&quot; and it is said can break existing code and
it does but the reason why it's needed is still unclear to us.

We have scalar datasets of compound types, here is an example 
of one dataset definition:

DATASET &quot;/Configure:0000/ControlData::ConfigV1/Control/config&quot; {
   DATATYPE  H5T_COMPOUND {
      H5T_STD_U8LE &quot;uses_duration&quot;;
      H5T_STD_U8LE &quot;uses_events&quot;;
      H5T_COMPOUND {
         H5T_STD_U32LE &quot;seconds&quot;;
         H5T_STD_U32LE &quot;nanoseconds&quot;;
      } &quot;duration&quot;;
      H5T_STD_U32LE &quot;events&quot;;
      H5T_STD_U32LE &quot;npvControls&quot;;
      H5T_STD_U32LE &quot;npvMonitors&quot;;
   }
   DATASPACE  SCALAR
   DATA {
      ....................
   }
}

In 1.3.0 I could access it very naturally:

&gt;&gt;&gt; ds = f[&quot;/Configure:0000/ControlData::ConfigV1/Control/config&quot;]
&gt;&gt;&gt; ds['events']
0L
&gt;&gt;&gt; type(ds['events'])
&lt;type 'long'&gt;

while in 2.0.1 I need to do more complex things:

&gt;&gt;&gt; ds = f[&quot;/Configure:0000/ControlData::ConfigV1/Control/config&quot;]
&gt;&gt;&gt; ds['events'](0L,)
&gt;&gt;&gt; type(ds['events'])
&lt;type 'numpy.void'&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt; ds['events'].dtype
dtype([('events', '&lt;u4')])
&gt;&gt;&gt; ds['events']['events']
0

The last thing is extremely confusing - why should it be necessary to
do the slicing operation twice just to get to a data? 

I did not try 2.1.0 but &quot;What's new&quot; in that version does not mention 
anything related. Could we please get old behavior back, it's much
more natural to use than 2.0.1?

Here is additional info:
- Your operating system - RHEL5
- Your Python version 2.4 for 1.3.0, 2.7 for 2.0.1
- h5py version '2.0.1'
- UNIX only: HDF5 version: '1.8.4'
- UNIX only: How you installed HDF5: yourself

Thanks,
Andy

